{"title":"LoRA Meets Dropout under a Unified Framework","domain":"LLM_NLP","seeds":[{"problem":"In LoRA-based parameter-efficient finetuning for transformers, it is unclear whether dropout methods designed for full finetuning remain effective and how different transformer-specific dropouts relate; with few trainable parameters, dropout’s role in mitigating overfitting appears contradictory and underexplored.","method":"The paper proves that DropKey and DropAttention have equivalent forward computations (when using normalized rescaling), but shows that the NoGrad operator in DropAttention injects gradient noise during backpropagation, harming stability and performance. Building on this, it proposes a unified framework with three axes—dropping position (attention logits/weights/hidden reps), structural pattern (element/column/span), and compensation for the train–inference gap (e.g., bidirectional KL vs. JS)—to systematically instantiate and compare methods under LoRA. Empirically, column-wise DropKey performs best, element-wise HiddenCut surpasses span-wise under LoRA, DropAttention performs worst due to gradient noise, and bidirectional KL consistently outperforms JS for compensation."},{"problem":"LoRA finetuning remains overfitting-prone and lacks a dropout method tailored to its constraints that is effective across NLU/NLG tasks and LLM scales.","method":"The paper introduces HiddenKey, which combines column-wise dropout of attention logits (DropKey-style) in self-attention with element-wise dropout of hidden representations in the feed-forward module, and adds a bidirectional KL divergence between two stochastic forward passes to reduce the train–inference gap. Across RoBERTa-large on GLUE, GPT-2 Medium on E2E/WebNLG, and LLaMA2-7B, HiddenKey consistently outperforms LoRA baselines and prior dropouts; adding input/output dropout yields no consistent additional gains, indicating the method’s sufficiency."}]}
